2022 was a year of insane growth, but also of regrowth, for me. I graduated with my Masters in Clinical Dietetics from USC, watched my little sister get married, saw some major expansion of my CPA Firm, got signed to an international modeling agency (and got some of my most cherished publications thus far), and even got to spend a little time traveling with my sweetheart (though we had to cancel two trips due to my injury). What this year most importantly taught me, however, was that sometimes things take time to get better. No matter how good of a situation you may be in, how much of an optimal (for you) diet/regimen you may maintain, how good of a healthcare team you may have, or even how well educated you may be in your own care - sometimes unfortunate things just happen. My spinal disc injury hasn’t fully recovered even still (though it is WORLDS better), and it was diagnosed on 9/17. Sometimes, you just have to support your body through the process, to do the right things and basically wait while the situation improves. Try not to climb up the walls too much. 😝

As we come into the new year (and always), please be wary of anyone who may try to sell you an instant fix for your healthcare concerns, whether they be physical or mental. There are unfortunately no guarantees in life, and absolutely no magic cure-alls. Your lifestyle is a multifaceted approach to health and wellness, and you need to approach all aspects of health to the best of your ability to feel the best you can. For me, my injurious problem was exercising too hard and not using proper body mechanics, but I also haven’t been giving myself enough time to unwind. Moving forward, things will be much more well-rounded. Just please remember that these things take time (I’m reminding myself of this too), and that there isn’t an end-date to living a healthy life. It’s also okay if you’re on a different chapter than someone else, and it’s super okay if your version of a healthy life doesn’t look like another person’s. Blessings to you all in the upcoming year. 23 is my lucky number so it’s gonna be a good one. 🍀

social_posts.post_text: Pride isn’t about advertising your preferences to people, or trying to convince anyone to practice new behaviors that they aren’t interested in. Pride is about, quite literally, being proud to be who you are regardless of your sexual orientation or gender identity. Why is it practiced? Because historically and even now, people tell LGBTQIA+ people that they should be ashamed to exist. We face ridicule, oppressive guidelines, and volatile accusations about our intention in being honest about who we are. Sexuality and gender are FAR more fluid concepts than much of the world would like you to believe, and literally NO ONE PERSON will have the capacity to love the exact same section of humans that you do. Your superpower, in these regards and in every other aspect of life, is that you are unique and different. Whether you’re straight, gay, bisexual, asexual, fluid, questioning, trans, cis, non-binary, bigender, or anything in between - be proud. Happy #pride 🏳️‍🌈🏳️‍⚧️

I’m so proud of what my body has been able to do in eight months. From a spinal disc injury leading me to being unable to even sit down for 8 weeks, to now being able to swim laps and build back stronger than ever before. It was very frustrating to go from a highly active lifestyle to walking 3k steps and lifting 8 pounds at most per day, but with a team of neurology experts (and my own resilience), I am stronger than I have ever been.

It look an exasperatingly long duration of building my core, strength training with the tiniest bands, and easing into more cardio as I could tolerate it, but I feel more powerful than I’ve felt in a really long time. 

I still have some recovering to go with my spine (it takes ages), but I’m staying the course and making it happen. From losing 180 pounds to prevent getting full-blown diabetes (already prediabetic) at 18, to overcoming a major sports injury, my body never ceases to amaze me with what it can endure. I’m very grateful to call it my home. It’s got dimples, lines, cellulite, and spots, and they’re my spots. I hope it carries me around for a long, long time. ❤️❤️

I’m officially a runway model, y’all!!! I got to walk my first #MiamiSwimWeek show this past Sunday, July 9th and I couldn’t be more excited for what’s in store next. Ended up walking for THREE designers and was requested by two more!

To the teenage me: you always knew you were going to be someone who would make a difference and you were right. You learned to live peacefully with your mental health struggles and developed a love for the world that is largely unmatched, with a mission to show others how beautiful it can be for them too - if they allow themselves to reach out and grasp it. We got all the way to the Miami swimsuit runway without removing our loose skin from the 180 pound weight loss to show others that they are beautiful without having to change (though change can be amazing if it’s for you first). We can show the world how to be confident, and how to love the skin you’re in. It’s okay to lose weight or have a baby and have some loose skin. It’s okay to have cellulite or be super skinny or curvy or have acne. That’s on being a unique human being. You’re f*cking gorgeous and can do pretty much anything you choose. This week we all won. 

👙: @katya_suzdaleva_designer

Not only did I get to start my runway career in 2023, I also got to OPEN my first show walking for designer @mojadocollection! Iam so fortunate to have a wonderful support system behind me: my family, my friends, my agencies, and amazing fellow models!

 However, right now I have to give a special shout out to my husband @ravi_ramnarain! All through #MiamiSwimWeek, he drove me around, helped me carry things, brought me snacks and ibuprofen, and stayed with me through my first show even after some of the photographers had gone home. We got to go grab some Taco Bell together afterward and then he drove me home in the pitch black at midnight across Alligator Alley, with probably 30 total streetlights in two hours. He got up quietly to let me sleep in a little (I didn’t, but how sweet), and then worked a full day after having piggybacked off of a trip to Springfield just a few days before the weekend. I always make damned sure he is well taken care of too, but this isn’t about me. 

Love like ours is once in a lifetime, if you’re lucky. A million thanks again to him, and to everyone who believes in me.

THIS BRAND was such an honor to walk for! @girlschronicallyrockclothing is a fashion brand that focuses on accessible fashion, or fashion for those with different physical abilities. As a person who is currently struggling with my own ability due to a lingering spinal injury, I never realized just how all encompassing self-care can be for chronic illness/injury until it happened to me. Many days per week, dealing with my healing spinal disc puts me in outfits that are comfortable and easy to put on, but aren’t necessarily what I’d actually like to be wearing. Not having easier to wear, fashionable clothes can feel isolating and can affect a person’s self-esteem - which can in turn lead to increased stress and potentially poorer health outcomes. 

I was able to put this bodysuit on without having to lie down, which is what I generally have to do to get dressed these days. It felt so empowering to just put it on! Accessible clothing will change the game for those with chronic pain, limited mobility, who are recovering from surgery, pregnant persons, and so many more. It is so incredible that this brand exists; accessibility is the new buzzword of fashion for a damned good reason. 💕🐆

I hope you give yourself permission to eat your favorite foods this Thanksgiving weekend. Don’t feel guilty about taking time away from work or for eating too many calories. I know the world expects us to be the most optimal, present, energetic version of ourselves all the time and that can lead to guilt when you step away or don’t regiment your diet the most ‘optimal’ way. The holidays are meant to be a time to be present in your interpersonal relationships and to share one of the most intimate offerings we have as a society - food - with one another. Hug your loved ones and put the food guilt on the shelf. Count your blessings in food and hugs. Times are tough, but life is still full of good memories for the making. Be present this weekend, please. 🖤
